# Release Note

Write every release note in two parts, in this strict order.

## Delta analysis (before drafting)

- Take the **full commit set** for the release window (e.g. since the previous release tag), not isolated commits one by one. Several commits may improve, replace, or partially revert others **within the same window**; only the **net shipped state** matters for readers.
- Describe the **final vision** of features and changes—what users and operators actually get in **this** release—not intermediate steps, churn, or implementation timelines.
- **Bug fixes**: include fixes that matter when upgrading **from the prior shipped release**. Omit fixes that only correct problems introduced **during this same release cycle** and never existed in that prior release.

## 1) Priority section for end users (always first)

- Start with changes that have direct impact for end users.
- Avoid technical jargon in this section.
- Highlight features, user value, and business outcomes.
- Organize this section by major business domains of the app:
  - Trips
  - Messaging
  - Activities
  - Expenses
  - Meals
- Include administrator-oriented items in this section only when they are true feature-level business value.

## 2) Complementary detailed section (technical / operations)

- Then add a more detailed section with a moderate technical level.
- Include items here that were not listed in the first section.
- Include bug fixes, technical adjustments, and administrator-oriented changes **when they belong in the shipped delta** (see **Delta analysis**).
- Keep the writing clear and structured without losing product readability.

## Style rules

- Prioritize clarity and business impact over implementation details.
- Present information from most important to most detailed.
- Keep a concise, value-oriented tone.
- As a .md file, added to the repo root
- Use french language all the way.
